Headline::::
When Saturday Comes still shooting from football’s fringes




DateTime::::2016-03-11T20:59:00+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">T</span></span>here was a slightly odd incident a few years back when I worked at the football fanzine When Saturday Comes. Early one morning there was a knock at the door and a Very Popular Well Known TV Presenter came in and started saying things like “Hi! … Lads … All right? Yeah. Just filming upstairs … Lads! So. Yeah Hi!”</p>

<p>There was a bit of slightly baffled nodding and smiling. It wasn’t really a popping-in kind of office. But Very Popular Well Known TV Presenter seemed nice. Eventually he went away. So, er, do you know him then, someone said after a while. No. Do you? … Oh right. Odd. Seems … OK though.</p>

<p>A few hours later there was another knock. Lads! Hi! All right? Great! …Great. Listen, we’re doing this filming and, well, I just wondered if it would be OK for …” And so a little later, in an atmosphere of mild, tolerant bemusement, Very Popular Well Known TV Presenter was installed in the editor’s chair, WSC T-shirt on, bookcases groaning behind him, doing his piece to camera.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/when-saturday-comes-blog/2016/feb/10/respect-season-ticket-holders-stadiums">How to earn respect from established season ticket holders: shut up and wait</a> </p>

<p>The programme went out a while later. In isolation it would have been possible to infer that Very Popular Well Known TV Presenter was indeed – though he doesn’t make a thing of it, naturally – the beating, throbbing heart of the 1980s punk-football zine crossover scene, dispensing his kindly words of wisdom like a great steaming Toby jug full of wonderfully warming bovril-flavoured piss.</p>

<p>In the years since, when people have asked how you get on in the media, I sometimes remember that afternoon and think, yeah, that’s how you do it. Showing a bit of brass neck. Transparently name-dropping left-of-centre football magazines in an attempt to assume an implied gravitas and borrowed sense of cool. I mentioned, I think, that this all happened when I used to work at When Saturday Comes.</p>

<p>It should be said that Popular Well Known TV Presenter is clearly a decent chap and has been a high-profile friend to the mag since. Which is no small thing for an independent magazine kept afloat by its long-standing subscribers, and which celebrates its own 30th anniversary this month.</p>

<p>Every few years these WSC-still-Standing pieces tend to appear, each time with the same unspoken, fearful subtext that this might even be the last of them. By now the early days of WSC are well rehearsed. An offshoot of the music fanzine Snipe, first published from a semi-derelict shed in Upper Clapton Road, it was conceived by the journalist Mike Ticher and then developed with the current editor Andy Lyons.</p>

<p>What seems odd now is its complete novelty at the time. In an era when football has smeared itself across every surface it seems inconceivable that until March 1986 nobody had really thought of producing a concerted alternative voice to the cramped daily pars of the back pages or <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/sep/06/alan-hansen-match-of-the-day-horrible" title="">the avuncularities of Match of the Day</a>, that the most common alternative literature on sale at football matches was the odd National Front magazine.</p>

<p>There is a founding irony in WSC’s invention as a response to this, sparked mainly by a sense of mild irritation at football’s marginalisation, its portrayal as an outsider activity, preserve of boot boys and knuckle-draggers. The early years often involved taking a stand against the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/feb/12/hillsborough-inquest-hears-chief-constable-fans-blamed-for-deaths" title="">institutionalised disdain for supporters</a> in the wake of Hillsbrough and other disasters. And beyond simply making the point that people who are interested in football can also be interested in things like music and books and films, that this is an activity that also deserves a place in the light.</p>

<p>Albeit, as an early-teenage reader the important stuff in the middle always seemed secondary to the fun bits at either end. Firstly the covers, my favourites of which are probably the famous, trailblazing Hillsborough one from June 1989, when WSC carried the strap-line “Unanimous verdict” over pictures of the FA’s Graham Kelly saying “it wasn’t our fault, the police (“It wasn’t our fault”), Margaret Thatcher (“It wasn’t our fault”) and finally a crowd shot of some fans saying “Oh well it must be our fault again.” Plus of course the one with a huge entirely unrelated picture of the teenage Ryan Giggs and the headline RYAN GIGGS: IS HE BEING USED TO SELL MAGAZINES?</p>

<p>The real gold was at the back though in the directory of club fanzines that seemed to take you off on a secret tour of the country. Blind, Stupid and Desperate (Watford). When Skies Are Grey (Everton). The City Gent (Bradford). The Square Ball (Leeds). Sick In The Basin (Partick Thistle). Fly Me To The Moon (Middlesbrough). Brian Moore’s Head Looks Uncannily Like The London Planetarium (Gillingham). The Leyton Orientear. Dial M For Merthyr. Finisterre. Fisher. German Bight. It’s like a slightly angry football version of the shipping forecast.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/when-saturday-comes-blog/2015/dec/15/punjabi-wolves-fans-group-culture-molineux">Meet Punjabi Wolves, the fans' group bringing culture and noise to Molineux</a> </p>

<p>It is customary at this stage to credit WSC and its co-fanzines as a founding spark for a certain kind of voice, a way of writing and speaking about football that is there now in the explosion of blogs and fan sites. Certainly a huge cast of football writers, formats, TV shows and politicised ways of looking at the sport have spun out of its rather raw beginnings.</p>

<p>Above all it is a curious irony that a magazine founded to offer a way out of the fringes has in fact ended up spending the vast majority of its life in the Premier League era, protesting not about marginalisation but often the exact opposite, aspects of a sport that has turned itself inside out for television, marketing, profiteering owners and all the rest.</p>

<p>Which was the point, I suppose, about Very Popular And Famous TV Presenter, the ghost at the door, spawned in good faith by that same impulse, an emblem of the slightly Skynet aspect of the world WSC helped to make. Not that this is an entirely worthy enterprise, or indeed one without fangs. Perhaps the most famous piece of recent times was a <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/42-Media/145-no-love-no-joy" title="">review of Tim Lovejoy’s autobiography</a> by Taylor Parkes, a long‑time WSC writer. Perfectly realised in its eloquent, calm, unarguable disdain for every single fibre of the Lovejoy entertainment persona. It’s still out there doing the rounds, a definitive advertisement for the eternal values of scepticism and creative dissent.</p>

<p>For now WSC remains a kind of conscionable voice at the fringes, a hospitable place, selling you only a magazine, some jokes, and a sympathetic voice for everyone from ad hoc contributors to the terrifyingly well-informed pedants of the letters page. Let it always be there!</p>




