Author::::gerardpeter
DateTime::::2016-03-12T08:11:40Z
I still read WSC but not as avidly as back in the day. Then it had an amateurish and sparky relevance - just like early rock fanzines and like the other club fanzines mentioned. But now it needs an upgrade if not a remake. I can see without some interest in football you would not give it a second glance, but I am not sure how many "real fans" read it. Ronay mentions online forums- a different world mate: vitriolic and vindictive and dodging the libel laws, but passionate and also often extremely funny. Contrast last year Blades supporters' forums with the liberal - and even anti-football - agenda followed by the main stream press and WSC. It does cover "the game" in out of the way places - Bratislava's third tier - and historical blind spots - Finnish top flight, review of the season 1988-9. It also does serious stuff on grass roots football - but who would go to read this? Junior coaches, football administrators, Trevor Brooking? Some of the writing is as cliched as anything knocked up by Tim Lovejoy - Harry Pearson being a case in point. The letters' page offers anorak-like pedantry as readers compete to be snarky about Mark Lawrenson and, yes, Tim Lovejoy. The front covers are still good - never fail to make me laugh. But it is a fringe publication and not for all the right reasons.



